File: Domestic workers challenged the legislation, saying it infringes on their rights. eNCA JOHANNESBURG - Domestic workers can now claim compensation for injury, death or disease suffered while on duty since 1994. The Constitutional Court upheld a High Court ruling, declaring a section of the Compensation for Occupational Injuries and Diseases Act unconstitutional. Domestic workers challenged the legislation, saying it infringes on their rights. READ: Injury claims on the cards for domestic workers The court says their exclusion has a stigmatising effect. It also says domestic workers remain severely exploited, undermined and devalued. The court ordered the Labour Department to pay the costs of the case.